[] void:class ceonq:QuantityInterval ;
    void:propertyPartition [ rdfs:label "has distribution"@en ;
            void:classPartition [ void:class futuram:UniformDistribution ] ;
            void:property futuram:hasDistribution ;
            rdfs:comment "The probability-distribution the Monte-Carlo aggregator samples this quantity interval from — a futuram:Distribution (subclass of the Apollo continuous parametric probability distribution) carrying the shape parameters its kind requires. Required: a quantity IS a distribution, so its shape is mandatory. Pairs with futuram:hasBestValue (the centre); the interval min/max endpoints remain an optional informational spread." ],
        [ void:classPartition [ void:class qudt:QuantityValue ] ;
            void:property ceonq:hasMaximalValueIncludedOfInterval ],
        [ void:classPartition [ void:class qudt:QuantityValue ] ;
            void:property ceonq:hasMinimalValueIncludedOfInterval ],
        [ rdfs:label "has best value"@en ;
            void:classPartition [ void:class qudt:QuantityValue ] ;
            void:property futuram:hasBestValue ;
            rdfs:comment "The central best point estimate of a quantity interval — the single representative value (a qudt:QuantityValue with numericValue and unit). REQUIRED on every interval, so a statement always carries one representative number; the included min/max endpoints (the spread) are OPTIONAL. The Monte-Carlo aggregator centres each statement's sampled distribution on this best value, using the min/max endpoints as the spread and the stated distribution kind (futuram:hasDistribution) as the shape; with no min/max it treats the statement as a point (delta). CEON's QuantityInterval has no central/best/nominal value term (only interval endpoints), so this is a FutuRaM addition reusing the same QUDT value pattern. Neutral as to which statistic it is (mean, median or mode); it is the value to use when one number is needed." ] .

